| MLB Says Slingbox Illegal, CEA Thinks Otherwise                    |
|   from the media-ing-on-the-fly dept.                              |
|   posted by Zonk on Thursday May 31, @17:25 (Television)           |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/31/2121206              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

The Tie Guy writes "Sling Media's Slingbox allows consumers to watch and
control their home television programs from a remote PC or smartphone â€” a
process called '[0]placeshifting'. Content owners are typically edgy when
it comes to the placeshifting topic. However, most don't view Slingbox as
an imminent threat that will destroy the commercial broadcast model.
[1]Major League Baseball is going against the grain by saying that
Slingbox owners who stream home games while traveling are breaking the
law because it allows consumers to circumvent geographical boundaries
written in to broadcast deals. This has sparked a huge debate that has
the MLB, baseball fans, and the CEA up in arms. CEA President Gary
Shapiro doesn't agree, and is coming to the defense of Sling Media and
place-shifting in general."

